---
description: Prefer variable validation over Terraform check blocks for input rules
globs: "**/*.tf"
alwaysApply: false
---

# Terraform input validation

When validating module **inputs**, use `validation` blocks on `variable` definitions in `variables.tf`. Do not use `check` blocks for rules that only involve variables.

## Use `validation` on variables for

- Required combinations of variables (e.g. `private_network_id` required when a flag is true)
- Mutually exclusive options (e.g. only one connectivity mode)
- Format or range constraints on variable values

```hcl
# variables.tf — preferred

variable "enable_public_endpoint" {
  type    = bool
  default = false

  validation {
    condition     = var.enable_private_endpoint != var.enable_public_endpoint
    error_message = "enable_private_endpoint and enable_public_endpoint cannot both be true."
  }
}

variable "private_network_id" {
  type     = string
  nullable = true

  validation {
    condition     = !var.enable_private_endpoint || var.private_network_id != null
    error_message = "private_network_id must be set when enable_private_endpoint is true."
  }
}
```

## Use `check` only when necessary

Reserve `check` blocks for assertions that depend on **resource or data source attributes** after refresh (computed values, provider behaviour). If a rule can be expressed with variables alone, do not use `check`.

```hcl
# Avoid — input-only rule belongs in variables.tf
check "private_network_id_required" {
  assert {
    condition     = !var.enable_private_endpoint || var.private_network_id != null
    error_message = "..."
  }
}

# Acceptable — depends on computed resource state
check "example_after_apply" {
  assert {
    condition     = length(aws_example.main.ids) > 0
    error_message = "Resource returned no IDs: ${jsonencode(aws_example.main)}"
  }
}
```

When in doubt, prefer `validation` in `variables.tf` and omit redundant `check` blocks.
